sf_trees <- readr::read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2020/2020-01-28/sf_trees.csv')

Introduction

The data set contains information on tree species, their locations (address, latitude, and longitude), the date it was planted, some of its measurements, and other variables. Some of the data is missing (obviously).

Cleaning

In a new data frame trees, I remove first removed tree_id (a unique identifier).

trees <- sf_trees %>% 
  select(-tree_id)

Species

There are 192,987 trees of 571 species. Some of them are hybrids (e.g., Acer x), some are locally adapted (e.g., Prunus cerasifera and Prunus serrulata types), some are missing genus and/or family names. It appears that subspecies are mostly grouped together. There is a whole group of Tree(s):: and :: that must have not been identified.

nrow(trees)
[1] 192987
trees %>% 
  group_by(species) %>%
  tally()

The species variable is pretty complicated and messy. First, I remove all the cases where there was no species recorded. I am sorry to exclude those trees but if we dont know the species, the observation is not useful to us at all. This leaves us with 179,519 trees of 569 species.

trees <- trees %>% 
  filter(species != "::" & species != "Tree(s) ::")

nrow(trees)
[1] 179519
trees %>% 
  group_by(species) %>%
  tally()

Location

There is redundant information in the address and in the latitude and longitude variables. First, I remove all the observations that do not have address, latitude or longitude. This removed 1637 trees.

Looking at the combination of address, latitude and longitude variables, there is some redundancy. The variable address is

trees %>% 
  group_by(address, latitude, longitude) %>% 
  tally()
